This music game has smooth, vibrant graphics, works perfectly in 18:9 ratio and an intuitive level up system to unlock more songs. Controls are simple, either tap on the screen's right (ground attack) or left side (for air attacks). You control a character that stays 'fixed' on a moving surface, which feels more intuitive than tapping all over the screen. The songs all have, so far, Japanese lyrics and even your character has Japanese lines at the end of the level and on the start screen. Nice change from the regular lyric-less pieces we get with most music games. The difficulty rating, I find to be lower than e.g. Cytus 1 or TapTapRevenge, which makes Muse Dash less frustrating and more fun.

It's a fun new spin on rhythm games, but there are two main issues I would 
like to address: lading time and music desync. The game's loading screen 
takes up 15 to 30 seconds (not just me, my friends who play this have slow 
loading times as well), which is bad for a rhythm game because you lose 
your momentum while playing. As for the music desync, it doesn't always 
happen, but the fact that it does is bad, especially since this is a rhythm 
game. Note that this happens whether I wear headphones or not. Side 
comments are the UI can be enhanced and the animations could be more fluid. 
But overall when the bugs doesn't happen, this is a fun, really fresh take 
on rhythm games.

This is a great rhythm game to get into if you're new to rhythm games. Even 
for a less than casual rhythm gamer, it's still very fun. It's not overly 
complicated nor over the top in mechanics. The songs are great if you like 
upbeat songs. The graphics are super cute, and the animation is great for 
how simple it is. The controls are easy, and (this is where it's great for 
beginners) you don't need to track the notes all over the screen, which can 
be fun, but it seems like half the new rhythm games are moving in that 
direction. It's a great game, and totally worth the price even if it's not 
on sale.
